snippet.textDisplay: I’m a dog groomer and I had to learn a lot about their behavior before becoming certified. We have to be able to identify when a pup is scared or upset. It’s for our safety and theirs. I see everyone pointing out that the dogs are smiling. When a dog smiles and breathes heavily it usually isn’t a good thing. Sometimes it means that they’ve gotten exercise and they’re sweating or thirsty, but these pups are in bed, in a relaxed setting, so it may indicate that they’re stressed out or anxious. Pacing, panting, heavy breathing, and putting ears down are all signs of stress. The black and white pupper seems pretty aware that Jeffree is upset. The way he lays on his back to let Jeffree pet his tummy is so sweet. My dog would do the same thing. It shows that they’re being vulnerable. It’s a way to distract us. Out of all of the dogs, he seems to want to comfort Jeffree the most. Pomeranians already have a tendency of breathing kinda heavy, so when they’re upset they can turn into little furry balls of panic. Jeffree has probably been very distraught, but his pups are doing a really good job at staying calm and watching over him. Dogs are smart and a lot more intuitive than people think they are. 🖤
